description.plain:
Marvin Gaye was one of the most consistent and enigmatic of the Motown hitmakers, with a career that exemplified the maturation of black pop into a sophisticated form spanning social and sexual politics.

Blessed with a mellifluous tenor and a four-octave vocal range, Gaye was among the most gifted composers and singers of his era. His life ended tragically on April 1, 1984, only one day before his 45th birthday, when he was shot to death by his father.

description.plain:
What’s Going On is an exquisite plea for peace on Earth, sung by a man at the height of crisis. In 1970, Marvin Gaye was Motown’s top male vocal star, yet he was frustrated by the assembly-line role he played on his own hits.
- Rolling Stone’s Top 500 Songs

songs.full_title: Sexual Healing by Marvin Gaye
songs.title: Sexual Healing

description.plain:
Released in 1982, “Sexual Healing” is one of Marvin Gaye’s most popular songs, and his last to reach the top 20 in the US, UK and Australia. It won the Grammy Award for Best Male R&B Vocal Perfomance and the instrumental version won Best R&B Instrumental Perfomance. In 2003, Rolling Stone listed it as one of the best songs of all time.

Recorded in Ostend, Belgium in 1982, the song represented a comeback for Marvin to the American music scene. The singer had been living overseas to escape two divorces, tax scandals and to overcome a debilitating cocaine addiction and depression. The  song was borne out of a comment made by songwriter David Ritz’s when he visited Gaye and saw he had pornography spread across his coffee table:

‘Marvin, this is some sick [expletive]. What are you doing? What you really need is sexual healing.’

A plaque commemorating Marvin Gaye’s stay in Ostend, Belgium, was placed in front of the apartment where he lived.

songs.full_title: Let's Get It On by Marvin Gaye
songs.title: Let’s Get It On

description.plain:
“Let’s Get It On” is a deceptively simple declaration of sex-positivity, released at a time when such statements were revolutionary.  It is even more impressive when one considers that it was created by a man awakening from the trauma of growing up constantly physically and emotionally abused by a preacher father who conditioned his children to regard sex as shameful.  That father, Marvin Gaye Sr., would infamously murder his son in 1984.

The song celebrates a turning point for the younger Marvin, who first learned to play music in the church and at one point endeavored to follow in his father’s footsteps as a minister.

In “Let’s Get It On,” Marvin is still making spiritual music, but this time to elevate the act of physical love and exalt it as an expression of a living person’s potential on Earth.

It topped both the US Pop and R&B charts in the summer of 1973 and was also successful in Canada and the UK.
